://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dustyslaunchpad>Dustys Launchpad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/16/03 4:16:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=231.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Orion Vs Liberty ship-Who’s the Daddy?</span><hr size=1> Orion Vs Liberty ship-Who’s the Daddy?<br>
<br>
No contest really, but that’s not to say that Liberty ship is in any way inferior. Liberty (or something very like it) is absolutely essential for the colonisation of the solar system. Orion may be the Daddy of heavy lift launchers, (and I really don’t believe anything else can ever come close) but without a durable large capacity and reusable SSTO the whole project is dead in the water.<br>
<br>
Orion’s great strength is not her ability to travel quickly around the solar system, there are plenty of other ways to do that now, and other ways are under development. What Orion can give us is the ability to build, on earth (i.e. without all that faffing about in space suits and zero g) huge structures weighing hundreds of thousands or even Millions of tons, Factories, Habitats, Ore and chemical processing plants, hydroponics facilities and even shipyards and then to launch them into orbit and deliver them to their destinations as turnkey projects, possibly even complete with their crews. Moon, Mars and Asteroid bases would not have to be painstakingly built out of thousands of pieces ferried from earth at enormous expense and assembled in hostile conditions nor (initially) painstakingly constructed out of local materials (In the longer term this would be the aim but much time, money, effort and lives would be saved by getting the initial infrastructure there in one piece)<br>
<br>
Orion’s great weakness is that She is not very reusable. She can take off, She can fly around for a while and She can land (Earth would be a bit scary but the Moon or Mars should be OK) and that’s about it! For all its mass the pusher plate is a rather delicate structure and though it would be quite capable of providing a landing shock absorber, bouncing it onto a planets surface would certainly damage it beyond repair. Even if it didn’t there is the problem of how we launch the ship high enough to fire the first pulse unit when we try to take off again.<br>
<br>
Orion is, unquestionably, the Daddy, but we also need Liberty, Hotol and Space elevators. None of these concepts should be seen as competing with one another. They are all part of the same picture.<br>
<br>
Dusty<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1822<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/16/03 4:33:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=231.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Orion Vs Liberty ship-Who's the Daddy?</span><hr size=1> Very good points.  The key to space expansion may rest in the space elevator.<br>
