<br>
I envision orbital facilities where Orion will be assembled after it is sent up piece by piece via elevator (avoiding the political risk of a nuclear orion launch from earth).  The Orion could fly around, and be serviced at the end of each mission.  We could build a fleet of Orions for different uses-mining, asteroid management, commerce, exploration, etc.  <br>
<br>
An SSTO would be necessary as well-an HTOL to take goods and people quickly to orbit-thus, the spaceplanes will be like the airplanes of today, and the elevator will be like the trains.  The elevator would be cheaper and for larger loads, while the SSTO will be faster, and for smaller loads.  A spaceplane could be used as a long distance airplane as well (hopefully, we will have maglev soon for  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1825<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/16/03 6:58:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=231.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Orion Vs Liberty ship-Who's the Daddy?</span><hr size=1> I agree, Congress should have term limits...Now, just try convincing them to vote themselves out of a job. <br>
Limits can also cause complacency in the incumbent.  The problem is that no politician thinks beyond the next election.<br>
That means no long term planning or projects... Colonizing space is a long term project.<br>
<br>
The biggst problem with the space elevator hauling Orion parts is that the pusher plate may need to be a single unit, <br>
and as such very massive, on the order of 1000 tons in weight or more... which may be above space elevator capability. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zentrander>Zentrander</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 176<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/16/03 7:03:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=231.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Orion Vs Liberty ship-Who's the Daddy?</span><hr size=1> could we send it in pieces to an assembly plant? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 136<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/16/03 8:09:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=231.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Orion Vs Liberty ship-Who's the Daddy?</span><hr size=1> I do not know exactly how much of Orion's orbital velocity could be bled off by aerodynamic drag, as with, say, the Apollo capsules, but it has to be on the same order. That is, the Orion could be slowed to low subsonic velocity (.5 mach or less) just by drag. The pusher plate is a very good re-entry shield in both composition and shape. What do we do from there? The minimum drag velocity can be approached at a fairly high altitude. Drive bombs can be fired until the vertical velocity is below the minimum increment for another bomb, say, 100 fps or less. (any more and it starts accelerating back toward space) <br>
Orion's great strength is its lifting power. Among other things, it can easily carry enough chemical rocket motors, and fuel, to lower itself gently from the aerodynamic and bomb-braking minimum. It wouldn't take much. For a 10,000 ton Orion, 15,000 tons of thrust could stop the vehicle from 100 fps in 6 seconds. With an isp of just 300, these motors would use about 300 tons of propellant in that time. More would be necessary, since it may not be possible to time the chemical rocket burn to exactly match touchdown, but not a lot more. For landings on lighter bodies, the thrust requirement is lower. For deceleration on the moon, the bombs would have to be used down to the minimum increment, with the chemical rocket array used below that. <br>
<br>
If we land on the Earth itself, we will probably need to use rocket braking all the way down from the drag minimum. I think that .5m is very conservative for this figure (certain early ballistic missile RVs slowed to .45 m without being designed for maximum deceleration). A higher ISP for the braking rockets could also reduce the propellant requirement. This would be especially likely in later stages of exploration, when the craft can fill its propellant tanks with water-derived  LH2/LOX at the destination point. With the 300 isp, 1500 tons would be required for the most conservative case, rocket braking on Earth from .5m with an additional 500-1000 tons being needed as a safety margin. This is a lot for a 10,000 Orion but well within its capability, leaving several thousand tons for payload. Even with 1/5 of its liftoff mass taken up by braking propellant, Orion is still far superior to any other system in payload/mass ratio.   <br>
<br>
