As for risk, sure.  I followed yales good advice and simply planned for a worst case scenario.  In that case, the total radiation released would be at most twice as much as was released in Chernobyl, but it would be released at worst 6000 kilometers West of South America, out over the Pacific.<br>
<br>
Nothing out there to hurt, really, since the vast majority of the risk from Chernobyl was caused by radioactive iodine uptake from milk drunk shortly after the release.  The fallout would be diluted into harmlessness by the mighty Pacific.  I am confident the Pacific can handle this due to the successful risk mitigation of the CASTLE series of nuclear tests, which released several hundred times as much radioacative byproducts as a total Liberty Ship failure could.  And hopefully, losing a Liberty Ship entirely wouldn't be more than a once a year thing.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
As for aborts, there aren't many.  Even in the event of the loss of six engines, the Liberty Ship can still make orbit by running the surviving thrusters for a longer time.  After yales harped on common mode failures I decided to mount the central engine on a hard mount, with no gimballing and the simpler plumbing that entails, so a software fault won't take out all the engines.  It is possible to only gimbal 4 of the engines and solidly mount three of them.  OR, if we're truly paranoid, we can eliminate gimbaling entirely and do all our attitude control with the maneuvering jets.  <br>
<br>
(Ok, I am being a trifle facetious.  It can only withstand the loss of two engines in the first 60 seconds of flight.   And losing two engines in the first second would require the dumping of large amounts of cold gas from the maneuvering thrusters to maintain flight orientation and directional stability.  Fortunately, it has 12 pods of 5 reaction jets, just for this sort of event, and it carries a LOT of reaction mass.)<br>
<br>
In addition, since the cargo is carried in a detachable pod on the nose, it is possible to ditch the cargo on the way up then make a controlled landing of the fuel vaults and crew.  (The nuclear thrusters and fuel vaults are designed to be restartable.)<br>
<br>
If the Liberty Ship loses all of it's thrusters, it can still generate almost 1000 meters per second of deltaV by bleeding off the hydrogen in the main tank.  This would allow the ship to make a controlled re-entry and ditch in the deep ocean in almost any loss of power scenario.  <br>
<br>
If the main hydrogen tank explodes, the thrust structure is a solid piece at the aft of the ship, containing all of the fuel vaults.  All radioactive materials are placed into the vaults and the reaction pods that are attached to the thrust structure use the local tanks of neutronically warmed hydrogen to make a controlled re-entry, and a ditch into the deep ocean is arranged if at all possible.  If a ditch onto land is completely unavoidable, the fuel vaults are aerobraked using the thrust structure to the lowest possible velocity and impacted in the most uninhabited area that can be reached.<br>
<br>
Please note, these are risk mitigation scenarios that entail flying down chunks of the ship AFTER it has been blown to pieces, which is a pretty extreme scenario, but somewhat less catastrophic than pulverizing the entire ship into scrap.<br>
<br>
Oh, the crew rides up inside one or more lifepods, which are patterned on an Apollo capsule with a cold hydrogen jet manuevering pod attached.  If the Liberty Ship gets utterly trashed, the crew can hopefully eject inside these capsules and ride back down to Earth.<br>
