<br>
Yes, the Sea Dragon is puny and weak.<br>
<br>
Let me see if I can make you see why I say this.<br>
<br>
The Sea Dragon was designed with a sky-high launch thrust of 80,000,000 pounds.  It had a launch weight of a &quot;mere&quot; 40,000,000 pounds.  Why was it accelerating SO HARD?<br>
<br>
For a hint, note the tiny mass fraction to orbit.  Think of gravitational losses.  I would dare say that if it accelerated less savagely, it wouldn't get any cargo to orbit at all, as the increased gravity losses would eat up it's entire cargo capacity.<br>
<br>
As a side effect, the Sea Dragon has a VERY rough ride, leaving the water at two gravities and hammering along at over 5 g's at first stage burnout.  This means any cargo going up on it has to be built to survive a much harder ride than the Space Shuttle, which peaks at 3 gravities.<br>
<br>
The Liberty Ship, on the other hand, never exceeds 2 gravities in a simple full throttle to orbit launch profile, and could have a maximum g load of a meager 1.4 if you want to throttle down the thrusters on the way up.<br>
<br>
Also, note that the Sea Dragon has a TINY cargo fraction.  Most commonly it is quoted as 1,200,000 pounds to orbit.  With a launch mass of 40,000,000 pounds that means that only 3 percent of the rocket makes it to orbit, and the cargo is probably not all of that since some kind of a kick stage would probably be needed.  <br>
<br>
The Liberty Ship takes almost exactly 66 percent of its liftoff mass to orbit, or 4.4 million pounds.  Of that 4.4 million pounds, 2 million is defined as cargo.  The rest of it is the Liberty Ship and the fuel it needs to get back down.<br>
<br>
In comparison, the Sea Dragon is indeed puny and weak, since the Liberty Ship has a mass fraction 22 times higher.<br>
<br>
